  "sections": {
    "Background": {
      "text": "Also known as Leptomeningeal Carcinomatosis or leptomeningeal metastasis (LM)\nUncommon and late complication of solid tumors and hematological cancers, approximately 5-8% and 5-15% respectively\nMost common primary tumors associated with LM are breast, lung, and melanoma\nCommonly misdiagnosed due to symptoms mimicking infectious\nmeningitis\nand chronic\nheadache",
      "subsections": {
        "Pathophysiology": {
          "text": "Multiple routes tumor cells can gain access to CSF\nMost commonly thought to be through hematogenous spread via arachnoid vessels or direct extension from brain parenchyma",
          "tables": []
        }
      },
      "tables": [],
